<DOCNO> AP880529-0026 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
is it live or is it bosendorfer 
a rocket scientist and a robotics expert using a 9foot piano 
have teamed up to create an instrument that can record every 
flicker of a virtuosos finger and then improve on it 
the bosendorfer 290 se imperial grand looks like a piano next to 
a computer but behind the keyboard optical sensors tiny electric 
motors and three linked computers form the guts of a frighteningly 
accurate musical instrument 
invented by a wayne stahnke a scientist from the national 
aeronautics and space administrations jet propulsion laboratory in 
pasadena calif the bosendorfer is played like any piano inside 
the instruments are recording even microscopic motions 
once the pianist walks away a punch of a few computer buttons 
brings forth the performance just played depressing the piano keys 
and pedals exactly as the musician did but the bosendorfer can 
also improve on the performance 
in its most straightforward mode the piano listens to a 
live piano performance remembers that performance note for note 
and then reproduces that performance on the very instrument upon 
which that performance was played said john amuedo a recording 
engineer who worked on artificial intelligence projects at the 
massachusetts institute of technology 
the potential for the 100000 instrument a sort of player 
piano for the computer age was immediately apparent to pianist 
frederick moyer and composerproducer gunther schuller who are 
collaborating on the first recording using the bosendorfer 
because the piano records its own performance not with 
microphones but with tiny optical and electronic sensors the 
sometimesdisturbing background noise that can crop up at a live 
performance has no impact on a recording made on the bosendorfer a 
subway car could clatter through the concert hall and it wouldnt 
matter 
once a performance is over the hall could be cleared and the 
performance could be played amid silence or the piano could be 
shipped to a recording studio where the keys could be punched to 
bring forth the performance with all its spontaneity and energy but 
none of the background noise 
with the push of a few computer keys the handlers of the 
bosendorfer can correct the tiniest of errors mistakes inaudible 
to the human ear but visible among the numbers and symbols on the 
computer terminal 
it raises a kind of moral aesthetic question as to how perfect 
you want to make your recording said schuller you can make it 
so perfect that it becomes almost inhuman 
in march moyer performed mussorgskys pictures at an 
exhibition and several short pieces by mendelssohn at wellesley 
college afterward schuller and amuedo went to work on the editing 
and found on the computer screen the inevitable tiny errors that 
even the best of pianists make 
moyers performance the first cassette disc using the 
bosendorfer is to be released this fall on gm recordings 
amuedo defends the editing capabilities of the instrument as 
merely improving techniques already widely used by recording 
engineers record producers edit recordings heavily even live 
recordings he argues the bosendorfer merely makes the process 
easier and cleaner nor he said is the idea of a noteperfect 
recording anything new as anyone who has heard a player piano 
knows 
using existing techniques a pianist could play a passage 
beautifully but make one mistake correcting the error would 
require tossing out the wellplayed section and replaying it with 
the bosendorfer engineers merely have to plug in the correct note 
schuller also sees the bosendorfer as an unparalleled teaching 
tool pianists can listen to their own playing exactly as it sounds 
on the piano and the computer can slow down a performance without 
affecting the pitch of a note allowing pianists to judge their own 
execution of rapid passages 
amuedo is unconcerned the bosendorfer will kill the market for 
live performances with all their errors a tiny mistake passes 
unnoticed in a live performance he said on a record that is heard 
several times it can become an annoyance 
no amount of editing is going to salvage a musically bad 
performance amuedo said when vladimir horowitz gets up and 
plays he makes lots and lots of mistakes and yet still people pay 
20 and 30 to hear him play because he makes music out of those 
mistakes 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880529-0027 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a senior adviser to soviet leader mikhail s 
gorbachev charged at the start of summit talks sunday that the 
united states had rejected a pair of soviet proposals aimed at 
clearing the way for drastic reductions in longrange nuclear 
missiles 
the accusation came as gorbachev welcomed president reagan to 
the moscow summit with an appeal to end nuclear testing and 
preserve the 1972 antiballistic missile treaty which would limit 
the presidents star wars plan for a spacebased missile defense 
system 
reagan responded that us and soviet negotiators are making 
progress toward a treaty reducing strategic weapons by as much as 
50 percent citing other joint efforts to ease eastwest tensions 
the president said that our work has begun to produce results 
yevgeny velikhov vice president of the soviet academy of 
sciences told reporters that american negotiators had rejected 
kremlin proposals to ease the two countries impasse over star wars 
and verify limits on submarinelaunched cruise missiles 
the two issues are among the main obstacles to the proposed 
start or strategic arms reduction treaty being negotiated by us 
and soviet experts in geneva defense secretary frank carlucci 
dismissed any attempt to link star wars to progress on a start 
agreement 
national security adviser colin powell held out little hope of 
completing a treaty before reagan leaves office next january 
velikhov who has advised gorbachev on the star wars issue said 
the americans had rejected a soviet proposal to discuss what types 
of testing could be permitted under the 1972 abm accord 
that treaty limits each side to a missile defense at one site 
the joint statement issued after the reagangorbachev summit in 
washington last december said both sides would be allowed to test 
as required the united states said that allows tests of 
potential star wars weapons but the soviets disagree 
velikhov said that within the framework of the december 
statement we need to settle some technical questions but he 
charged that the americans want to destroy the treaty 
if the united states deploys a nationwide defense it will 
violate the abm treaty and jeopardizes effort to cut strategic 
offensive weapons velikhov said 
the two sides also agreed in december to negotiate ceilings on 
submarinelaunched nuclear missiles but not to include them in the 
6000warhead limit proposed for the strategic weapons treaty 
the soviets said velikhov have proposed monitoring the 
presence of nuclear warheads on submarinelaunched cruise missiles 
using devices to detect neutron and gammaray emissions 
american officials have rejected that idea they say it would be 
too easy to bypass such devices and that they oppose allowing 
soviet inspectors to board american submarines for onsite 
verification of any limits on the missiles 
gorbachev told reagan that it is incumbent on us to discuss 
constructively the main aspects of disarmament the set of issues 
related to 50 percent cuts in strategic offensive arms while 
preserving the 1972 abm treaty problems of eliminating chemical 
weapons reductions in armed forces and conventional armaments in 
europe cessation of nuclear testing 
us officials have repeatedly rejected gorbachevs appeals for 
an end to nuclear testing and refused to join an 18month soviet 
testing moratorium 
white house chief of staff howard baker said on nbctvs meet 
the press show that there could be a fifth summit meeting before 
reagan leaves office next january but only if the two sides 
reach agreement in start talks 
marshal sergei f akhromeyev chief of the soviet general staff 
said the two countries might be able to strike a start deal by the 
end of reagans second term 
my own personal opinion is that weve covered more than half 
the ground akhromeyev said in an abctv interview here 
powell said reagan would certainly like to see the start 
treaty completed during his term the broad outlines are there 
were now down in the trenches working out the very difficult 
issues having to do with verification and cruise and mobile 
missiles 
i would like to see some progress this week and progress is 
