pope john paul ii named 25 new cardinals 
from 18 countries sunday including prelates from lithuania and 
hong kong in a move to bolster the roman catholic church in the 
soviet union and china 
two americans archbishops james a hickey of washington and 
edmund c szoka of detroit were on the list 
the new princes of the church who will be formally elevated 
at a june 28 vatican session bring the number of cardinals to 161 
four new cardinals come from italy two each from the united 
states brazil spain and india and one each from canada 
mozambique colombia australia hungary cameroon austria 
france west germany mauritius hong kong switzerland and 
lithuania 
hickey 67 in a statement in washington said he was truly 
honored very humbled and deeply grateful to be chosen he said 
he would work with all those of good will to build a more 
just and caring community 
szoka 60 told a news conference in detroit that hes deeply 
moved and honored and will carry on the same functions whether 
im cardinal or not 
in announcing the appointments at the end of a mass in st 
peters basilica john paul noted that the new cardinals come from 
every continent reflecting the universality of the churchs 
860 million followers 
most of the new appointees were heads of large dioceses or 
vatican departments traditionally held by cardinals 
vatican officials described as especially significant the naming 
of cardinals for lithuania the catholic stronghold in the soviet 
union and hong kong a british colony that reverts to communist 
chinese rule in 1997 
these were courageous appointments vatican spokesman 
joaquin navarro told reporters these are not symbolic choices 
but options for the future 
as lithuanias first publicly named cardinal the pope chose 
vincentas sladkevicius 68 the apostolic administrator of 
kaisiadorys who was appointed president of the lithuanian epispocal 
conference in april 
from 1963 to 1982 he was impeded by soviet authorities from 
performing his religious duties and was virtually confined to his 
residence according to the vatican 
sladkevicius becomes the second resident cardinal in the soviet 
union julijans vaivods of latvia was elevated by john paul in 1983 
at least 2 million of lithuanias 35 million people are 
estimated to be roman catholics the pope who has frequently 
expressed his desire to visit his flock in the soviet union has 
publicly disclosed that at least on two occasions he has been 
refused permission to travel to lithuania 
the pope moved to bolster the church in china by elevating john 
baptist wu chengchung the 63yearold bishop of hong kong there 
has been no resident cardinal in china since the communists took 
over in 1949 
china cut ties with the vatican in 1957 and established a 
breakway catholic church which claims 3 million members an 
unknown number of other catholics remain secretly loyal to the 
pope and several are imprisoned for their religious practices 
the two us appointments bring to nine the number of american 
cardinals 
archbishop roger mahony of los angeles 52 was considered for 
promotion but passed over in what navarro acknowledged was a 
great exclusion for the american church the spokesman said 
mahony was not included because of his young age and was likely to 
become a cardinal at a later time 
named as the first cardinal in mozambique a marxist country 
that the pope will visit during his september tour of southern 
africa was alexandre jose maria dos santos archbishop of maputo 
the rev hans urs von balthasar a swiss theologian highly 
regarded by the pope was the only nonbishop among the 25 new 
cardinals 
in addition to voting in a papal conclave cardinals advise the 
pope serve on special vatican commissions and act as spokesmen for 
the church in their countries 
the number of cardinals under the age of 80 and therefore 
eligible to vote for a new pope will now number 121 one more than 
the limit set by church rules the vatican offered no immediate 
explanation however two of the cardinals will turn 80 this summer 
