<TEXT>
the smell of success stinks say some 
residents of this eastcentral illinois town whose canneries supply 
food that stocks the nations cupboards 
each spring residents await the return of noxious fumes that 
waft off water used to process beans and corn at two local 
canneries that support the towns economy 
i just tell people it only hurts your nose it doesnt hurt 
your lungs said hoopeston chamber of commerce official rose 
buck thats the smell of success 
millions of gallons of the contaminated water are sprayed 
irrigationstyle onto nearby fields until winter weather arrives 
warm temperatures release the vapors and winds carry them around 
and into the town of 6400 residents 
while canning company officials say special equipment has 
helped the odor leaves many breathless 
there is nothing more offensive than the bean water said 
hoopeston city councilman willis bird who farms near the ponds 
sitting along illinois rts 1 and 9 you dont get used to it 
you just hope youre not in that field too long 
but the putrid smell best described as rotting vegetables 
represents money in the bank for the townspeople 
two centuryold hoopeston canneries owned by pillsburyjoan of 
arc canning co and stokely usa inc employ hundreds of local 
residents and pump millions of dollars into the areas economy 
thousands more migrant seasonal workers are hired each year to help 
with the fall harvest 
if we dont have that smell we would be in trouble bird 
said adding that most americans probably dont realize what 
hoopeston endures to keep canned goods in the nations grocery 
stores 
they dont even know where a can of beans comes from they 
dont know where milk comes from or how much work is done to keep 
the beans clean he said 
nine types of beans come into the pillsburyjoan of arc plant 
dry and must be washed and then soaked and softened in water most 
of the water is then discarded 
the rehydrated beans including kidney garbanzo and blackeyed 
peas are sold to consumers nationwide under the joan of arc and 
other labels and used in chili sold by the wendys hamburger chain 
plant manager gary kortkamp of pillsburyjoan of arc says the 
company invested in a 1 million stateoftheart water 
reclamation facility three years ago that eliminated much of the 
odor 
the system strains the larger bean parts out then pumps the 
water into tanks where microscopic organisms eat much of the 
remaining bean matter 
im talking about a relative smell kortkamp said on a 
scale of one to 10 we have improved it to an eight or nine 
but some odor remains bird said 
after they have processed it two or three times then it gets 
into that big lagoon out there then they spray it into the air and 
it gets a little rank he said 
in the fall fumes from water used to process sweet corn 
contribute to the odor problem pungent corn water then is sprayed 
onto fields north of town 
stokely sells the corn and a variety of other canned goods under 
its label 
while the scent might annoy some vistors many longtime 
residents say its all in the nose 
that doesnt stink a hoopeston policeman said when asked 
about the smell ive lived here all my life and im used to it 
